    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-12-04T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-12-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="479"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d479">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Hopkins Papers</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Assistant Secretary of War</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_MJJ1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Mccloy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Presidents Special Assistant</hi>
                        (<persName corresp="#p_HHL1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hopkins</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-12-04">4 December
                            1943</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Memorandum for Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HHL1">Harry
                            Hopkins</persName>
                    </hi>:</p>
                <p>There is an increasing indication that the British are not now inclined to go
                    along with the arrangement I made with <persName corresp="#p_EA1"
                        >Eden</persName>.<note n="1" xml:id="d479fn1">See <persName
                            corresp="#p_MJJ1">McCloy</persName>’s memorandum of November 30, 1943,
                        to <persName corresp="#p_HHL1">Hopkins</persName>, <hi rend="italic"
                            >ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_447">p. 447</ref>.</note> They are placing
                    the blame on the War Cabinet.</p>
                <p>It is important that the arrangement we agreed to stick, but it will not be done
                    unless we take a strong position. Until they come through as originally
                    outlined, I propose not to send from Washington any military men to operate
                    either on the European Commission<note n="2" xml:id="d479fn2">European Advisory
                        Commission.</note> or any transferred Combined Civil Affairs Committee in
                    London. I believe that <persName corresp="#p_WJG1">Winant</persName>’s
                    appointment should go through,<note n="3" xml:id="d479fn3">See <persName
                            corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName>’s telegram of December 3, 1943,
                        to <persName corresp="#p_HC1">Hull</persName>, <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>,
                            <ref target="#pg_784">p. 784</ref>.</note> but as soon as I indicated
                    that we would strengthen the London Committee with a good staff, they reverted
                    to their former position, and that position is basically wrong. The plan we
                    should adhere to is attached.<note n="4" xml:id="d479fn4">The attachment is a
                        copy of the draft agreement printed <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref
                            target="#pg_446">p. 446</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Sincerely,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MJJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">John J. McCloy</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
